The effect of fences on the multi-mode contact networks on Michigan farms¶

This analysis examines the effect of wildlife fences on the multi-mode contact networks in Michigan farms.

Load in the contact data for analysis¶

After loading the data, we exclude all individuals that had proximity loggers, but never had any type of contact over the course of the study. The results of the analysis are robust to dropping these individuals.

In [3]:
# Load in formatted contact data
dat = pd.read_csv("../data/formatted/formatted_contact_data.csv")

# Load in unique contact data
unqids = pd.read_csv("../data/formatted/unique_contact_ids.csv", header=None).values.ravel()
unqids2 = np.unique(np.concatenate([dat.id1, dat.id2]))

# IDs that never had any contacts with troughs or otherwise despite being collared
nocontacts = set(unqids2) - set(unqids)

# Drop collared individuals that never had any contacts...only include active nodes
reddat = dat[~(dat.id1.isin(nocontacts) | dat.id2.isin(nocontacts))]

Reformat the data to consider three types of contact:

  1. Direct contact
  2. Indirect contact via stored feed
  3. Indirect contact via non-stored feed

# Melt by contact type
datdt = reddat.melt(id_vars=['pairID', 'season', 'fence', 'id1', 'spp1', 
                          'startid1', 'endid1', 'id2', 'spp2', 'startid2', 
                          'endid2', 'overlap_days', 'seasonal_overlap_days', 'farm'], 
                 value_vars=['direct_contacts', 'indirect_contacts_stored_feed', 'indirect_contacts_other'],
                 var_name="contact_type", value_name="contacts")

datdt.loc[:, "contact_score"] = np.nan
datdt.loc[datdt.seasonal_overlap_days == 0, "contact_score"] = -1 # No overlap

datdt.loc[(datdt.seasonal_overlap_days != 0) & (datdt.contacts == 0), "contact_score"] = 0

datdt.loc[(datdt.seasonal_overlap_days != 0) & 
          (datdt.contacts != 0) & 
          (datdt.contact_type == "direct_contacts"), "contact_score"] = 1

datdt.loc[(datdt.seasonal_overlap_days != 0) & 
          (datdt.contacts != 0) & 
          (datdt.contact_type == "indirect_contacts_stored_feed"), "contact_score"] = 2

datdt.loc[(datdt.seasonal_overlap_days != 0) & 
          (datdt.contacts != 0) & 
          (datdt.contact_type == "indirect_contacts_other"), "contact_score"] = 3

# Remove data with fencing and not in spring because this data was not collected over the
# full season.
datdt = datdt[~(datdt.season.isin(['winter', "summer", "fall"]) & (datdt.fence == 1))]

# Only include three farms in the fence comparison. Farm Bev is excluded as no cows had active proximity loggers
# after fence installation.
datdt = datdt[datdt.farm.isin(['joe', 'pete', 'styma'])]

Summary of contact types in the spring before and after fence installation

-1 : No logger overlap

0 : No contact

1 : Direct contact

2 : Indirect contact via stored feed

3 : Indirect contact via other resources

Exploring the effect of fence on the contact networks¶

In [6]:
# Drop bev from analysis
farmdt = datdt#[datdt.farm == "pete"]
animals = set(['moo', 'raccoon', 'opossum', 'deer'])

# Only include animal on animal interactions, direct or indirect
moddat = farmdt[(farmdt.contact_score > -1) & (farmdt.spp1.isin(animals) & farmdt.spp2.isin(animals))]

# Make species pair covariates
spppair = np.array(["_".join(np.sort([sp1, sp2])) for sp1, sp2 in zip(moddat.spp1, moddat.spp2)])
moddat = moddat.assign(spppair=spppair)

# Make design matrices. Different design matrices for different types of contact
_, Xmat1 = dmatrices("contact_score ~ " + " + ".join(["C(spppair)", 
                                                  "standardize(seasonal_overlap_days)",
                                                  "C(season)",
                                                   "fence",
                                                   "C(farm) + fence:C(farm)"]), 
                                        moddat, return_type="dataframe")

_, Xmat2 = dmatrices("contact_score ~ " + " + ".join(["C(spppair)",
                                                  "standardize(seasonal_overlap_days)",
                                                  "C(season)",
                                                   "fence",
                                                   "C(farm) + fence:C(farm)"]), 
                                        moddat, return_type="dataframe")

# Response variable as a multinomial vector
Yres = pd.get_dummies(moddat.contact_score)


fence_model = pm.Model()

with fence_model:
    
    # Transformed coefficients
    betad = pm.Normal('betad', mu=0, sd=2, shape=(Xmat1.shape[1], 1))
    betai_stored = pm.Normal('betai_stored', mu=0, sd=2, shape=(Xmat2.shape[1], 1))
    betai_other = pm.Normal('betai_other', mu=0, sd=2, shape=(Xmat1.shape[1], 1))

    # Softmax transformation with no contact as baseline
    etad = tt.exp(tt.dot(Xmat1, betad))
    etai_stored = tt.exp(tt.dot(Xmat2, betai_stored))
    etai_other = tt.exp(tt.dot(Xmat1, betai_other))
    
    # Calculate probabilities for multinomial model
    p_d = etad / (1 + etad + etai_stored + etai_other)
    pi_stored = etai_stored / (1 + etad + etai_stored + etai_other)
    pi_other = etai_other / (1 + etad + etai_stored + etai_other)
    pn = 1 - p_d - pi_stored - pi_other
    ps = tt.stack([pn, p_d, pi_stored, pi_other], axis=1).reshape((len(Yres.values), 4)) # Stack column-wise
    
    #print(ps.tag.test_value.shape)
    #print(betaD.tag.test_value.shape)
    #print(p_d.tag.test_value.shape)
    #print(p_i.tag.test_value.shape)
    #print(p_n.tag.test_value.shape)

    Y_obs = pm.Multinomial("Y_obs", n=1, p=ps, observed=Yres.values)
    
    fit = pm.sample(draws=3000, chains=3, init="advi", nuts_kwargs={'target_accept': 0.9})

Fit the full random effects model with an effect of fence¶

In [7]:
# Drop bev from analysis
importlib.reload(contact)
farmdt = datdt
animals = set(['moo', 'raccoon', 'opossum', 'deer'])

# Only include animal on animal interactions, direct or indirect
moddat = farmdt[(farmdt.contact_score > -1) & (farmdt.spp1.isin(animals) & farmdt.spp2.isin(animals))]

# Make species pair covariates
spppair = np.array(["_".join(np.sort([sp1, sp2])) for sp1, sp2 in zip(moddat.spp1, moddat.spp2)])
moddat = moddat.assign(spppair=spppair)

# Make design matrices. Different design matrices for different types of contact

# Note: removing  C(spppair):C(farm) gives identical fence results and drastically speeds up
# convergence.
_, Xmat1 = dmatrices("contact_score ~ " + " + ".join(["C(spppair) + C(spppair):C(farm)", 
                                                  "standardize(seasonal_overlap_days)",
                                                  "C(season)",
                                                   "fence",
                                                   "C(farm) + fence:C(farm)"]), 
                                        moddat, return_type="dataframe")

_, Xmat2 = dmatrices("contact_score ~ " + " + ".join(["C(spppair) + C(spppair):C(farm)",
                                                  "standardize(seasonal_overlap_days)",
                                                  "C(season)",
                                                   "fence",
                                                   "C(farm) + fence:C(farm)"]), 
                                        moddat, return_type="dataframe")

Xmat1_shared = theano.shared(Xmat1.values)
Xmat2_shared = theano.shared(Xmat2.values)

# Response variable as a multinomial vector
Yres = pd.get_dummies(moddat.contact_score)

fullids = pd.concat([moddat.id1, moddat.id2])
a1, lookup = contact.coerce_index(moddat.id1, fullids)
a2, _ = contact.coerce_index(moddat.id2, fullids)
num_ids = len(fullids.unique())

# Generate fence model
fence_model = contact.random_effects_model2_stored_feed(Xmat1_shared, Xmat1_shared, Xmat1_shared, Yres, a1, a2)

with fence_model:
    fence_fit =  pm.sample(draws=3000, chains=3, init="advi", nuts_kwargs={'target_accept': 0.9})

As suggested by Reviewer 1, try including a deer and "other"-wildlife effect of fence. That way we won't have to distinguish between raccoons and opossums (which we don't have much power to do), but can still try to identify an effect of fencing on deer.

# Drop bev from analysis
importlib.reload(contact)
farmdt = datdt
animals = set(['moo', 'raccoon', 'opossum', 'deer'])

# Only include animal on animal interactions, direct or indirect
moddat = farmdt[(farmdt.contact_score > -1) & (farmdt.spp1.isin(animals) & farmdt.spp2.isin(animals))]

# Make species pair covariates
spppair = np.array(["_".join(np.sort([sp1, sp2])) for sp1, sp2 in zip(moddat.spp1, moddat.spp2)])
moddat = moddat.assign(spppair=spppair)

# Make deer-other covariates. If interaction has deer assign 1 otherwise 0.
deerind = (moddat.spppair.str.find("deer") != -1).astype(np.int)
moddat = moddat.assign(whitetail=deerind)

# Make design matrices. Different design matrices for different types of contact

# Note: removing C(spppair):C(farm) gives identical fence results and drastically speeds up
# convergence.
_, Xmat1_wt = dmatrices("contact_score ~ " + " + ".join(["C(spppair) + C(spppair):C(farm)", 
                                                  "standardize(seasonal_overlap_days)",
                                                  "C(season)",
                                                   "fence",
                                                   "C(farm) + fence:C(farm)"]), 
                                        moddat, return_type="dataframe")

# Just include an effect of whitetail on fence with stored feed.
_, Xmat2_wt = dmatrices("contact_score ~ " + " + ".join(["C(spppair) + C(spppair):C(farm)",
                                                  "standardize(seasonal_overlap_days)",
                                                  "C(season)",
                                                  "fence + fence:whitetail",
                                                  "C(farm) + fence:C(farm) + fence:whitetail:C(farm)"]), 
                                        moddat, return_type="dataframe")

Xmat1_shared_wt = theano.shared(Xmat1_wt.values)
Xmat2_shared_wt = theano.shared(Xmat2_wt.values)

# Response variable as a multinomial vector
Yres = pd.get_dummies(moddat.contact_score)

fullids = pd.concat([moddat.id1, moddat.id2])
a1, lookup = contact.coerce_index(moddat.id1, fullids)
a2, _ = contact.coerce_index(moddat.id2, fullids)
num_ids = len(fullids.unique())

# Generate fence model
fence_model_wt = contact.random_effects_model2_stored_feed(Xmat1_shared_wt, Xmat2_shared_wt, Xmat1_shared_wt, Yres, a1, a2)

with fence_model_wt:
    fence_fit_wt =  pm.sample(draws=3000, chains=3, init="advi", nuts_kwargs={'target_accept': 0.9})

Plot the effect of fence on different farms for all contact types¶

In [34]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 1, figsize=(6, 5), sharey=True)

letters = ['A.', 'B.', "C."]

fit = fence_fit

contact_type = ['betad', 'betai', 'betai2']
cols = [Xmat1.columns, Xmat1.columns, Xmat1.columns]
plusminus = [-0.005, 0.005]
labels = ['Direct contact', 'Indirect contact via stored feed', 'Indirect contact via other resources']
nms = ['joe', 'pete', 'styma']
farmid = {'bev': "Farm A", 'joe': 'Farm B', 'pete': 'Farm C', 'styma': 'Farm D'}

handles = []
mean_probs = {}
probs_fence = []
probs_nofence = []

# Make a plot for both direct and indirect interactions
for j, ct in enumerate(contact_type):

    mean_probs[ct] = {}
    betad = fit[ct]
    betad = betad.reshape(betad.shape[0], betad.shape[1])
    intnames = cols[j]

    # Extract the farm and fence coefficients
    fenceind = pd.Series(intnames).str.find("fence") != -1
    fencenms = np.array(intnames)[fenceind.values]

    # Compute the effect of fence for each farm
    fencecoef = betad[:, fenceind.values]
    base = fencecoef[:, 0]
    other = fencecoef[:, 1:]
    additive = np.concatenate([base[:, np.newaxis], base[:, np.newaxis] + other], axis=1)

    probs_fence.append(np.exp(additive))

pms = [-0.1, 0, 0.1]
colors = ['white', 'gray', 'black']
for j in range(3):

    # 
    coefs = pd.DataFrame(np.log(probs_fence[j]), columns=nms)
    xvals = range(3)

    for m, col in enumerate(coefs.columns):
        vals = coefs[col].values
        lower, med, upper = stats.scoreatpercentile(vals, (2.5, 50, 97.5))
        print("{0}, {1}, {2}, {3}".format(col, lower, med, upper))

        ax.errorbar(xvals[m] + pms[j], med, yerr=[[med - lower], [upper - med]], marker='o', 
                                markersize=10, color=colors[j], ecolor="black", markeredgecolor="black")

    #sns.violinplot('variable', 'value', data=coefs.melt(), ax=axes[j])
ax.set_xticks(xvals)
ax.hlines(0, -2, 4, linestyle="--")
ax.set_xlabel("", size=12)
ax.set_xticklabels([farmid[c] for c in coefs.columns], size=12)


ax.set_ylabel("ln(proportional) change in probabilty of contact\n after fence installation",
                      size=12)
#ax.set_title(labels[j])
#ax.text(-0.1, 1.05, letters[j], ha="center", size=15, transform=axes[j].transAxes)
ax.set_xlim(-0.5, 2.5)

lines = [plt.Line2D([1], [1], color=colors[j], marker='o', linestyle="", 
                        markeredgecolor="black", markersize=10) for j in range(3)]
ax.legend(lines, labels, loc="lower left")
ax.text(-0.05, 1.05, "A.", size=15, ha='center', transform=ax.transAxes)

plusminus = [-0.005, 0.005]
labels = ['Direct contact', 'Indirect contact\nby stored feed, not deer', 'Indirect contact\nby stored feed, deer', 'Indirect contact\nby other resources']
nms = ['joe', 'pete', 'styma']
farmid = {'bev': "Farm A", 'joe': 'Farm B', 'pete': 'Farm C', 'styma': 'Farm D'}

handles = []
mean_probs = {}
probs_fence = []
probs_nofence = []

# Make a plot for both direct and indirect interactions
for j, ct in enumerate(contact_type):

    mean_probs[ct] = {}
    betad = fit[ct]
    betad = betad.reshape(betad.shape[0], betad.shape[1])
    intnames = cols[j]

    # Extract the farm and fence coefficients for non deer interactions
    fenceind = (pd.Series(intnames).str.find("fence") != -1) & (pd.Series(intnames).str.find("whitetail") == -1)
    
    # Compute the effect of fence for each farm
    fencecoef = betad[:, fenceind.values]
    base = fencecoef[:, 0]
    other = fencecoef[:, 1:]
    additive = np.concatenate([base[:, np.newaxis], base[:, np.newaxis] + other], axis=1)

    if j == 2:
        fenceind_wt = (pd.Series(intnames).str.find("fence") != -1) & (pd.Series(intnames).str.find("whitetail") != -1)

        fencecoef_wt = betad[:, fenceind_wt.values]
        base_wt = fencecoef_wt[:, 0]
        other_wt = fencecoef_wt[:, 1:]
        additive_wt = np.concatenate([base_wt[:, np.newaxis], base_wt[:, np.newaxis] + other_wt], axis=1)
        additive = additive + additive_wt

    probs_fence.append(np.exp(additive))

pms = [-0.17, -0.05, 0.05, 0.17]
colors = ['white', 'gray', 'gray', 'black']
mstyles = ['o', 'o', '^', 'o']
for j in range(4):

    # 
    coefs = pd.DataFrame(np.log(probs_fence[j]), columns=nms)
    xvals = range(3)

    for m, col in enumerate(coefs.columns):
        vals = coefs[col].values
        lower, med, upper = stats.scoreatpercentile(vals, (2.5, 50, 97.5))
        print("{0}, {1}, {2}, {3}".format(col, lower, med, upper))

        ax.errorbar(xvals[m] + pms[j], med, yerr=[[med - lower], [upper - med]], marker=mstyles[j], 
                                markersize=10, color=colors[j], ecolor="black", markeredgecolor="black")

    #sns.violinplot('variable', 'value', data=coefs.melt(), ax=axes[j])

ax.set_xlabel("", size=12)

Simulate fence and no fence contact networks¶

Simulate how fence affects the structure of the contact network. Using the fitted model to simulate networks with and without a fence effect. Then comparing mean degree between these networks.

fencesim = []
for Ysim in [Ysim_fence, Ysim_nofence]:
    
    # Predicted contact list
    predcscore = [y[:, 0] == 0 for y in Ysim]
    
    pred_networks = {}
    moddat_dict = {}
    
    datdt_nobev = datdt[datdt.farm != "bev"]
    
    for p, farm in enumerate(datdt_nobev.farm.unique()):

        pred_networks[farm] = []

        # Clean the observed network
        redind = (datdt_nobev.contact_score > -1) & (datdt_nobev.spp1.isin(animals) & datdt_nobev.spp2.isin(animals))
        tdat = datdt_nobev[redind]

        # Include all seasons as we are considering all of the nodes in a farm in this simulation.
        seasonind = tdat.season.isin(['spring', 'winter', 'summer', 'fall'])
        farmind = tdat.farm == farm
        moddat = tdat[farmind & seasonind]
        spppair = np.array(["_".join(np.sort([sp1, sp2])) for sp1, sp2 in zip(moddat.spp1, moddat.spp2)])
        moddat = moddat.assign(spppair=spppair)

        # Build simulated network
        pnets = []
        for i in range(len(predcscore)):

            predc = moddat[predcscore[i][farmind & seasonind]]
            Gpred = nx.Graph()
            Gpred.add_nodes_from(np.unique(np.concatenate([moddat.id1, moddat.id2])))
            Gpred.add_edges_from(list(zip(predc.id1, predc.id2)))

            pnets.append(Gpred)

        # Save observed and predicted
        pred_networks[farm] = pnets
        moddat_dict[farm] = moddat
        
    fencesim.append(pred_networks)
